   508Ôćĺ/// When printed, the outermost context would be printed first and the lower
   509Ôćĺ/// level underlying causes would be enumerated below.
   510Ôćĺ///
   511Ôćĺ/// ```console
   512Ôćĺ/// Error: Failed to read instrs from ./path/to/instrs.json
   513Ôćĺ///
   514Ôćĺ/// Caused by:
   515Ôćĺ///     No such file or directory (os error 2)
   516Ôćĺ/// ```
   517Ôćĺ///
   518Ôćĺ/// Refer to the [Display representations] documentation for other forms in
   519Ôćĺ/// which this context chain can be rendered.
   520Ôćĺ///
   521Ôćĺ/// [Display representations]: Error#display-representations
   522Ôćĺ///
   523Ôćĺ/// <br>
   524Ôćĺ///
   525Ôćĺ/// # Effect on downcasting
   526Ôćĺ///
   527Ôćĺ/// After attaching context of type `C` onto an error of type `E`, the resulting
   528Ôćĺ/// `anyhow::Error` may be downcast to `C` **or** to `E`.
   529Ôćĺ///
   530Ôćĺ/// That is, in codebases that rely on downcasting, Anyhow's context supports
   531Ôćĺ/// both of the following use cases:
   532Ôćĺ///
   533Ôćĺ///   - **Attaching context whose type is insignificant onto errors whose type
   534Ôćĺ///     is used in downcasts.**
   535Ôćĺ///
   536Ôćĺ///     In other error libraries whose context is not designed this way, it can
   537Ôćĺ///     be risky to introduce context to existing code because new context might
   538Ôćĺ///     break existing working downcasts. In Anyhow, any downcast that worked
